00:14:45,584 --> 00:14:47,074
That's not gonna happen.

220
00:14:48,687 --> 00:14:50,382
Not even a discussion?

221
00:14:50,589 --> 00:14:55,549
Billy, even if you could afford him,
respectfully, we love him.

222
00:14:55,761 --> 00:14:57,695
We're not about to let him go.

223
00:14:57,929 --> 00:14:59,863
You got this Venezuelan kid
coming up.

224
00:15:00,065 --> 00:15:02,363
We had him.
We moved him to Detroit.

225
00:15:03,735 --> 00:15:05,134
What else you thinking?

226
00:15:06,338 --> 00:15:07,862
Outfielders.

227
00:15:08,073 --> 00:15:10,735
- To replace Damon?
- Yeah.

228
00:15:10,942 --> 00:15:15,572
- In your price range? No disrespect.
- Enough, Mark.

229
00:15:16,681 --> 00:15:18,308
Hollins?

230
00:15:20,385 --> 00:15:22,910
- García?
- No.

231
00:15:23,121 --> 00:15:24,816
Maybe Coste.

232
00:15:27,793 --> 00:15:29,317
That's it.

233
00:15:30,695 --> 00:15:33,960
- All right, tell me about García.
- To replace Johnny Damon?

234
00:15:34,666 --> 00:15:37,635
- Mark, is he healthy?
- Yeah, he's healthy-ish.

235
00:15:37,836 --> 00:15:40,270
He had that back thing.

236
00:15:40,472 --> 00:15:43,202
- He'll be ready for spring ball.
- I'll tell you what.

237
00:15:43,408 --> 00:15:45,876
I can give you Guthrie
if you kick in some cash.

238
00:15:46,077 --> 00:15:47,101
- Mark Guthrie?
- Yeah.

239
00:15:47,312 --> 00:15:49,405
- How much cash?
- Two hundred K.

240
00:16:05,797 --> 00:16:07,162
Okay.

241
00:16:08,200 --> 00:16:12,000
- So García's gonna be a no.
- You're kidding me, right?

242
00:16:12,971 --> 00:16:15,269
- You're kidding me.
- I'm not.

243
00:16:16,975 --> 00:16:20,206
Okay. Straight up, García for Guthrie,
no kicker.

244
00:16:21,279 --> 00:16:23,873
- No kicker?
- Straight up.

245
00:16:27,252 --> 00:16:31,814
I think it's gonna be a hard no
on García, but let's just keep going.

246
00:16:32,023 --> 00:16:35,220
- What else you thinking?
- What are we doing? Is this business?

247
00:16:35,427 --> 00:16:37,657
This is the way we do business
in Cleveland.

248
00:17:21,506 --> 00:17:22,871
Hey.

249
00:17:24,109 --> 00:17:26,600
- Hello.
- Who are you?

250
00:17:29,481 --> 00:17:31,415
I'm Peter Brand.

251
00:17:32,350 --> 00:17:34,045
What do you do?

252
00:17:35,487 --> 00:17:38,012
I'm special assistant
to Mark Shapiro.

253
00:17:38,223 --> 00:17:40,054
So, what do you do?

254
00:17:42,460 --> 00:17:45,896
Mostly player analysis right now.

255
00:17:46,097 --> 00:17:49,794
Been on the job long?
First job in baseball?

256
00:17:51,269 --> 00:17:53,635
It's my first job anywhere.

257
00:17:53,838 --> 00:17:56,238
- Wow, congrats.
- Thank you.

258
00:17:56,441 --> 00:17:59,035
First job. Whose nephew are you?

259
00:18:01,479 --> 00:18:03,276
Why does Mark listen to you?

260
00:18:05,951 --> 00:18:07,748
I don't think...

261
00:18:08,486 --> 00:18:10,818
I don't think he does very often.

262
00:18:12,290 --> 00:18:14,155
He just did.

263
00:18:16,261 --> 00:18:17,751
Well, in that circumstance...

264
00:18:17,963 --> 00:18:21,490
...I think he was more listening
to Bruce than myself.

265
00:18:22,901 --> 00:18:24,493
Who are you?

266
00:18:27,238 --> 00:18:29,433
I'm Peter Brand.

267
00:18:32,477 --> 00:18:35,503
I don't give a rat's ass
what your name is.

268
00:18:36,247 --> 00:18:38,374
What happened in there?

269
00:18:39,517 --> 00:18:41,781
What happened in that room?

270
00:18:42,253 --> 00:18:44,915
I'm not quite sure
what you're asking me, Mr. Beane.

271
00:18:45,123 --> 00:18:47,523
What did you tell Bruce?

272
00:18:48,693 --> 00:18:53,187
- I just told Bruce I like García.
- You like García. Why?

273
00:18:55,500 --> 00:18:57,161
Why?

274
00:19:02,273 --> 00:19:03,763
I don't know.

275
00:19:21,393 --> 00:19:24,260
There is an epidemic failure
within the game...

276
00:19:24,462 --> 00:19:27,022
...to understand
what is really happening.

277
00:19:27,232 --> 00:19:31,669
And this leads people who run
Major League Baseball teams...

278
00:19:31,870 --> 00:19:36,000
...to misjudge their players
and mismanage their teams.

279
00:19:40,645 --> 00:19:42,579
I apologize.

280
00:19:43,548 --> 00:19:44,537
Go on.

281
00:19:47,852 --> 00:19:52,983
Okay. People who run ball clubs,
they think in terms of buying players.

282
00:19:53,625 --> 00:19:58,153
Your goal shouldn't be to buy players.
Your goal should be to buy wins.

283
00:19:58,363 --> 00:20:01,696
And in order to buy wins,
you need to buy runs.

284
00:20:01,900 --> 00:20:03,925
You're trying
to replace Johnny Damon.

285
00:20:04,436 --> 00:20:06,028
<i>The Red Sox see Johnny Damon...</i>

286
00:20:06,237 --> 00:20:09,866
<i>...and they see a star
who's worth $7.5 million a year.</i>

287
00:20:10,075 --> 00:20:12,942
When I see Johnny Damon...

288
00:20:13,144 --> 00:20:15,442
...what I see is...

289
00:20:16,881 --> 00:20:20,282
...an imperfect understanding
of where runs come from.

290
00:20:21,019 --> 00:20:22,577
<i>The guy's got a great glove.</i>

291
00:20:22,787 --> 00:20:25,722
<i>He's a decent leadoff hitter.
He can steal bases.</i>

292
00:20:25,924 --> 00:20:28,256
But is he worth the $ 7.5 million
a year...

293
00:20:28,460 --> 00:20:30,587
...that the Boston Red Sox
are paying him?

294
00:20:30,795 --> 00:20:32,626
No. No.

295
00:20:33,231 --> 00:20:35,062
<i>Baseball thinking is medieval.</i>

296
00:20:35,266 --> 00:20:37,734
<i>They are asking
all the wrong questions.</i>

297
00:20:37,936 --> 00:20:42,066
And if I say it to anybody,
I'm ostracized. I'm a leper.

298
00:20:42,273 --> 00:20:47,210
So that's why I'm cagey
about this with you.

299
00:20:47,412 --> 00:20:48,401
That's why...

300
00:20:48,613 --> 00:20:52,515
I respect you, Mr. Beane,
and if you want full disclosure...

301
00:20:53,151 --> 00:20:57,554
...I think it's a good thing
that you got Damon off your payroll.

302
00:20:57,756 --> 00:21:02,250
I think it opens up all kinds
of interesting possibilities.

303
00:21:02,460 --> 00:21:05,520
- Where you from, Pete?
- Maryland.

304
00:21:05,730 --> 00:21:08,995
- Where'd you go to school?
- Yale. I went to Yale.

305
00:21:10,135 --> 00:21:13,002
- What'd you study?
- Economics.

306
00:21:13,705 --> 00:21:16,196
I studied economics.

307
00:21:19,778 --> 00:21:24,112
Yale, economics and baseball.

308
00:21:25,717 --> 00:21:27,912
You're funny, Pete.

309
00:21:50,842 --> 00:21:52,036
<i>Tell me, why Billy?</i>

310
00:21:52,811 --> 00:21:55,143
<i>What is it that makes him special?</i>

311
00:21:55,346 --> 00:21:59,009
<i>Very rare do you come upon
a young man like Billy...</i>

312
00:21:59,217 --> 00:22:02,311
...who can run, who can field,
who can throw, who can hit...

313
00:22:02,520 --> 00:22:04,078
...and who can hit with power.

314
00:22:04,289 --> 00:22:07,281
Those five tools,
you don't see that very often.

315
00:22:07,992 --> 00:22:10,859
<i>Most of the youngsters
that we have an interest in...</i>

316
00:22:11,062 --> 00:22:12,495
<i>...have one or two tools...</i>

317
00:22:12,697 --> 00:22:15,291
...and we're hoping
to develop an extra one.

318
00:22:15,500 --> 00:22:17,400
Your son has five.

319
00:22:17,602 --> 00:22:21,595
We're looking at a guy that's a
potential superstar for us in New York.

320
00:22:21,806 --> 00:22:23,637
<i>The time is now to get him started.</i>

321
00:22:23,842 --> 00:22:26,640
We're prepared to make
a sizable financial commitment.

322
00:22:26,845 --> 00:22:29,211
The Mets are gonna
stand behind Billy...

323
00:22:29,414 --> 00:22:32,713
...because we expect him
to be our big-league center fielder.

324
00:22:32,917 --> 00:22:34,976
This check here
represents the offer...

325
00:22:35,186 --> 00:22:38,519
...that the New York Mets
would be making to Billy.

326
00:22:38,723 --> 00:22:43,820
You do know that he's been accepted
to Stanford on a full scholarship?

327
00:22:44,028 --> 00:22:45,154
I do.

328
00:22:45,363 --> 00:22:47,763
So he can do both?

329
00:22:47,966 --> 00:22:52,266
Unfortunately, he can't do Stanford
and professional baseball.

330
00:22:52,470 --> 00:22:56,338
He would have to pick one
or the other.

331
00:22:56,541 --> 00:22:59,009
<i>If he wants to be center fielder
for the Mets...</i>

332
00:22:59,210 --> 00:23:01,041
<i>...wants to be a baseball player...</i>

333
00:23:01,246 --> 00:23:06,115
<i>...he really needs to accept this
as life's first occupation, first career.</i>

334
00:23:06,317 --> 00:23:10,014
We're all told at some point we can
no longer play the children's game.

335
00:23:10,221 --> 00:23:12,689
We just don't know
when that's gonna be.

336
00:23:13,224 --> 00:23:17,251
Some of us are told at 18, some of us
are told at 40, but we're all told.

337
00:23:17,929 --> 00:23:21,126
<i>But this is a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity.</i>

338
00:23:21,332 --> 00:23:22,356
We want you badly...

339
00:23:22,567 --> 00:23:25,866
...and we think that this amount
of money expresses that desire.

340
00:23:26,070 --> 00:23:29,403
<i>Billy, this is your decision,
and whatever that decision is...</i>

341
00:23:29,607 --> 00:23:32,075
<i>...you know it's fine
with your mother and I.</i>

342
00:23:42,987 --> 00:23:45,217
- Hello?
- Hey, it's Billy Beane.

343
00:23:46,057 --> 00:23:49,788
- Hey, what time is it?
- I don't know.

344
00:23:50,795 --> 00:23:54,925
Listen, would you have drafted me
in the first round?

345
00:23:55,133 --> 00:23:56,532
<i>What?</i>

346
00:23:56,734 --> 00:24:00,226
After I left,
you looked me up on your computer.

347
00:24:00,438 --> 00:24:02,736
Would you have drafted me
in the first round?

348
00:24:02,941 --> 00:24:05,842
<i>I did, yeah.
You were a good player.</i>

349
00:24:06,044 --> 00:24:08,239
Cut the crap, man.

350
00:24:08,446 --> 00:24:11,347
Would you have drafted me
in the first round?

351
00:24:12,050 --> 00:24:16,180
<i>I'd have taken you in the ninth round.
No signing bonus.</i>

352
00:24:17,021 --> 00:24:21,481
<i>I imagine you would've passed
and taken that scholarship.</i>

353
00:24:22,226 --> 00:24:24,091
Yeah.

354
00:24:27,732 --> 00:24:30,166
<i>Pack your bags, Pete.</i>

355
00:24:30,635 --> 00:24:33,627
I just bought you
from the Cleveland Indians.

356
00:24:47,418 --> 00:24:50,876
<i>- Is it attached to that clamp?
- Yeah, let me unhook it.</i>

357
00:24:59,364 --> 00:25:01,855
<i>- Slide it up right there. To the left.
- I did.</i>

358
00:25:02,066 --> 00:25:04,193
<i>- Yeah, yeah.
- Hang on, it's wet.</i>

359
00:25:04,402 --> 00:25:05,960
<i>Come on.</i>

360
00:25:27,759 --> 00:25:29,522
- Morning, Suzanne. Coffee on?
- Yes.

361
00:25:29,727 --> 00:25:31,058
Great.

362
00:25:31,696 --> 00:25:33,527
- Billy Beane's office.
- Hey.

363
00:25:33,731 --> 00:25:34,755
- Peter Brand.
- Billy.

364
00:25:34,966 --> 00:25:37,434
- How are...? Hi, how you doing?
- Nice to see you.

365
00:25:37,635 --> 00:25:40,160
Good to have you here.
Boy, you move in fast.

366
00:25:40,371 --> 00:25:43,204
Yeah, yeah.
I got here early this morning.

367
00:25:44,742 --> 00:25:46,869
- All moved in.
- Yeah.

368
00:25:47,612 --> 00:25:49,170
Yeah.

369
00:25:49,380 --> 00:25:51,348
Hey, Billy...

370
00:25:51,549 --> 00:25:54,416
...I wanted you
to see these player evaluations...

371
00:25:54,619 --> 00:25:56,746
...that you asked me to do.

372
00:25:57,755 --> 00:25:59,347
I asked you to do three.

373
00:26:00,291 --> 00:26:01,622
Yeah.

374
00:26:01,826 --> 00:26:04,351
- To evaluate three players.
- Yeah.

375
00:26:04,562 --> 00:26:06,496
How many did you do?

376
00:26:06,697 --> 00:26:08,631
Forty-seven.

377
00:26:09,567 --> 00:26:11,057
Okay.

378
00:26:12,003 --> 00:26:15,700
Actually, 51.
I don't know why I lied just then.

379
00:26:24,749 --> 00:26:27,149
Why don't you walk me
through the board?

380
00:26:28,619 --> 00:26:30,177
Thank you.

381
00:26:56,481 --> 00:26:58,506
Using this equation
in the upper left...

382
00:26:58,716 --> 00:27:01,776
...I'm projecting that we need to win
at least 99 games...

383
00:27:01,986 --> 00:27:04,113
...in order to make it
to the postseason.

384
00:27:04,322 --> 00:27:08,418
We need to score at least 814 runs
in order to win those games...

385
00:27:08,626 --> 00:27:11,652
<i>...and allow no more than 645 runs.</i>

386
00:27:16,834 --> 00:27:18,096
<i>What's this?</i>

387
00:27:18,302 --> 00:27:21,863
<i>This is a code that I've written
for our year-to-year projections.</i>

388
00:27:22,073 --> 00:27:25,668
<i>This is building in the intelligence
that we have to project players.</i>

389
00:27:25,877 --> 00:27:26,866
<i>Okay.</i>

390
00:27:27,078 --> 00:27:29,672
<i>It's about getting things down
to one number.</i>

391
00:27:30,181 --> 00:27:32,706
<i>Using the stats
the way we read them...</i>

392
00:27:32,917 --> 00:27:36,011
<i>...we'll find value in players
that nobody else can see.</i>

393
00:27:39,590 --> 00:27:40,852
<i>People are overlooked...</i>

394
00:27:41,058 --> 00:27:44,824
<i>...for a variety of biased reasons
and perceived flaws.</i>

395
00:27:45,029 --> 00:27:48,294
<i>Age, appearance, personality.</i>

396
00:27:48,499 --> 00:27:53,198
<i>Bill James and mathematics
cut straight through that.</i>

397
00:27:54,839 --> 00:27:58,104
<i>Billy, of the 20,000 notable players
for us to consider...</i>

398
00:27:58,309 --> 00:28:00,800
<i>...I believe
that there is a championship team...</i>

399
00:28:01,012 --> 00:28:04,140
...of 25 people that we can afford...

400
00:28:04,348 --> 00:28:07,476
<i>...because everyone else in baseball
undervalues them.</i>

401
00:28:07,685 --> 00:28:10,916
Like an island of misfit toys.

402
00:28:15,393 --> 00:28:18,590
<i>Billy, this is Chad Bradford.
He's a relief pitcher.</i>

403
00:28:18,796 --> 00:28:23,028
<i>He is one of the most undervalued
players in baseball.</i>

404
00:28:23,234 --> 00:28:26,169
<i>His defect is that he throws funny.</i>

405
00:28:27,038 --> 00:28:31,065
<i>Nobody in the big leagues cares
about him because he looks funny.</i>

406
00:28:31,275 --> 00:28:34,335
<i>This guy could be not just
the best pitcher in our pen...</i>

407
00:28:34,545 --> 00:28:37,912
<i>...but one of the most effective
relief pitchers in all baseball.</i>

408
00:28:38,115 --> 00:28:40,845
<i>This guy should cost $3 million
a year.</i>

409
00:28:41,052 --> 00:28:43,885
<i>We can get him for 237,000.</i>

410
00:29:07,845 --> 00:29:09,244
Billy.

411
00:29:10,781 --> 00:29:13,181
- That it?
- Yeah.

412
00:29:43,347 --> 00:29:44,678
Hey, Art.

413
00:29:44,882 --> 00:29:47,043
Can I talk to you
before you get started?

414
00:29:47,251 --> 00:29:49,651
- I'm a bit busy right now.
- I know.

415
00:29:51,589 --> 00:29:53,113
- I know.
- Okay.

416
00:29:53,324 --> 00:29:54,951
- Morning, everyone.
- Art.

417
00:29:55,159 --> 00:29:58,390
- Peter Brand. Nice to meet you.
- Where the hell's Pete?

418
00:29:58,596 --> 00:29:59,620
That's Pete.

419
00:30:00,564 --> 00:30:03,032
Grab a seat. I'll be right back.

420
00:30:04,602 --> 00:30:07,435
- All right, where did you say he's at?
- Okay. He's on...

421
00:30:08,172 --> 00:30:10,800
- Who's the kid?
- A friend of mine.

422
00:30:12,610 --> 00:30:15,511
I can't manage this team
under a one-year contract.

423
00:30:15,713 --> 00:30:17,476
Well, sure you can.

424
00:30:19,216 --> 00:30:21,309
No, I can't.

425
00:30:21,519 --> 00:30:24,044
Okay. I gotta put a team on the field.

426
00:30:24,255 --> 00:30:27,691
After that, I'll take a good long look
at your contract.

427
00:30:27,892 --> 00:30:31,157
Deal with the manager's contract,
then put a team on the field.

428
00:30:31,362 --> 00:30:35,731
At this moment, if a grounder's hit
to first, nobody's there to stop it.

429
00:30:36,567 --> 00:30:40,901
It's not easy doing what I do
under the cloud of a one-year contract.

430
00:30:41,105 --> 00:30:42,470
Okay, I understand that.

431
00:30:42,673 --> 00:30:44,607
- I've been there.
- I know you have.

432
00:30:44,809 --> 00:30:49,212
A one-year contract means the same
thing to a manager as to a player.

433
00:30:49,413 --> 00:30:51,574
There's not a lot of faith there.

434
00:30:51,782 --> 00:30:54,512
Which is strange
after a 102-win season.

435
00:30:55,586 --> 00:30:57,520
I see.

436
00:30:57,722 --> 00:31:02,022
If you lose the last game
of the season, nobody gives a shit.

437
00:31:04,128 --> 00:31:07,894
- So it's on me now?
- No, Art, it's on me.

438
00:31:08,099 --> 00:31:11,398
And the kid is the new assistant GM.

439
00:31:11,602 --> 00:31:13,593
- Okay.
- Okay, fellas.

440
00:31:13,804 --> 00:31:15,396
Hey, Billy.

441
00:31:25,816 --> 00:31:28,512
You can't deny his offensive output.
He can play.

442
00:31:28,719 --> 00:31:31,688
And we need people that can play.

443
00:31:37,928 --> 00:31:40,260
Who do you wanna talk about first?

444
00:31:57,081 --> 00:31:59,049
None of them.

445
00:31:59,817 --> 00:32:02,752
Billy, we got 38 home runs,
120 RBIs to make up for.

446
00:32:02,953 --> 00:32:05,285
Guys, you're still trying
to replace Giambi.

447
00:32:05,489 --> 00:32:08,947
I told you we can't do it,
and we can't do it.

448
00:32:09,560 --> 00:32:13,724
Now, what we might be able to do
is re-create him.

449
00:32:13,931 --> 00:32:16,900
- Re-create him in the aggregate.
- The what?

450
00:32:17,101 --> 00:32:19,831
Giambi's on-base percentage
was .477.

451
00:32:20,037 --> 00:32:24,440
Damon's on-base, .324.
And Olmedo's was .291.

452
00:32:24,642 --> 00:32:26,837
Add that up and you get...

453
00:32:29,513 --> 00:32:30,775
Do you want me to speak?

454
00:32:31,849 --> 00:32:33,680
When I point at you, yeah.

455
